#. type: Plain text
#, no-wrap
msgid "[[!meta title=\"Secure Boot certificates update\"]]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#, no-wrap
msgid "[[!toc startlevel=2]]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"If the **Secure Boot Update Needed** notification below appears when "
"starting Tails, it means that the Secure Boot certificates of this computer "
"need to be updated."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#, no-wrap
msgid "[[!img support/known_issues/secure_boot_certificates/secure_boot_update_needed.png class=\"screenshot\" alt=\"Notification: Secure Boot Update Needed\"]]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"Otherwise, Tails will no longer start on this computer after a future Tails "
"upgrade. We cannot predict when such an upgrade will occur, because the "
"timing depends on changes that Tails could inherit from Debian in any Tails "
"upgrade."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"After this change in Tails occurs, the computer might display a **Secure "
"Boot Violation** error or another error message when trying to start Tails."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#, no-wrap
msgid "Why is this happening?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"[[!wikipedia Secure Boot]] is a security measure that prevents starting "
"malicious operating systems on a computer. Most computers running Windows "
"have Secure Boot enabled. Linux distributions, including Tails, also support "
"Secure Boot."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"Since 2023, [[Microsoft has started replacing|https://support.microsoft.com/"
"en-us/topic/windows-secure-boot-certificate-expiration-and-ca-"
"updates-7ff40d33-95dc-4c3c-8725-a9b95457578e]] the Secure Boot certificates "
"originally issued in 2011. These older certificates begin expiring in June "
"2026."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"Tails has detected that the computer still has outdated Secure Boot "
"certificates and needs an update."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#, no-wrap
msgid "Updating the Secure Boot certificates"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"To update the Secure Boot certificates of the computer, restart its regular "
"operating system, Windows or Linux, and apply all available updates."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
msgid ""
"For Windows, select **Start&nbsp;▸ Settings&nbsp;▸ Windows Update&nbsp;▸ "
"Check for Windows updates**."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  See also [[Microsoft: Install Windows\n"
"  updates|https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/install-windows-updates-3c5ae7fc-9fb6-9af1-1984-b5e0412c556a]].\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
msgid "For Linux, such updates are applied by the [[!wikipedia fwupd]] daemon."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  Linux distributions that use the GNOME desktop automatically apply this\n"
"  update through GNOME Software.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#, no-wrap
msgid "Disabling Secure Boot"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"If the **Secure Boot Update Needed** notification persists when restarting "
"Tails, it means that the Secure Boot certificates of the computer are still "
"outdated."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"Instead of updating the certificate, you can also disable Secure Boot. Even "
"with Secure Boot disabled, the regular operating system should still start."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"You can usually disable Secure Boot through the BIOS settings of the "
"computer, but the procedure varies by manufacturer. To learn how to edit the "
"BIOS settings, search for the user manual of the computer on the support "
"website of the manufacturer."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"In the BIOS menu, find the **Secure Boot** setting and disable it. This "
"option is usually in either the **Security** tab, the **Boot** tab, or the "
"**Authentication** tab."
msgstr ""
